  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Syrian Refugee Crisis Protection Monitoring in Beqaa Valley and  South Lebanon</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">As Lebanon struggles to cope with the influx of more than a million Syrian refugees, and particularly as the sectarian elements of the Syrian conflict spill over into Lebanese communities, there is a clear need for neutral international humanitarian actors to play a role in monitoring and identifying protection risks affecting the refugee community and their surrounding host communities. The geographical spread and lack of monitoring mechanisms currently in place in Lebanon reduces the opportunity to identify and mitigate protection risks as well as ensure the provision of response services. Given their inherent vulnerability, the protection risks to persons with specific needs (e.g., children, women-headed households, older persons, persons with disabilities,
and persons with psychosocial needs) are particularly high. Those in need of assistance lack access to services, while service providers often have limited access to data involving the risks to refugees and vulnerable host communities, limiting the humanitarian response&#x2019;s capacity to advocate and adequately plan
for effective and targeted prevention and response interventions.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Mercy Corps will implement a protection monitoring project in nine districts in Beqaa Valley, Nabatiyeh, and South Lebanon Governorates, nearly two thirds of the country. The purpose of the project is to conduct systematic and in-depth monitoring, analysis and reporting of protection needs, gaps, and trends to identify protection risks involving persons of specific needs to deliver targeted services to them.</narrative>
  </description>
